'''María Ávila Serna''' (born 12 March 1973) is a [[Mexican people|Mexican]] lawyer and politician affiliated with the [[Ecologist Green Party of Mexico]]. She represents the [[III Federal Electoral District of Chihuahua|Third Federal Electoral District of Chihuahua]] in the [[Chamber of Deputies (Mexico)|Chamber of Deputies]] of the [[LXIII Legislature of the Mexican Congress]].<ref name="sil">{{cite web|title=Perfil del legislador|url=http://sil.gobernacion.gob.mx/Librerias/pp_PerfilLegislador.php?SID=&Referencia=9218955|publisher=Legislative Information System|accessdate=8 July 2016|language=Spanish}}</ref>

==Life==
Ávila Serna obtained her law degree from the [[Universidad Autónoma de Ciudad Juárez]] and served as a clerk on the Federal Mediation and Arbitration Board No. 55 from 1997 to 2003.<ref name="sil"/>

In 2003, a year after joining the PVEM,<ref name="diario"/> Ávila joined the legislature after being elected to the Chamber of Deputies of the [[LIX Legislature of the Mexican Congress|LIX Legislature]]. She sat on six commissions, including Special for Kids, Teens and Families; Care for Vulnerable Groups; and Population, Borders and Migratory Matters.<ref name="sil"/> In 2005, during her first term as a federal deputy, she became the president of the PVEM in Chihuahua, an office she would hold for six years.<ref name="sil"/>

From 2007–10 and 2013–15, Ávila served in the Chihuahua state congress (LXII and LXIV Legislatures). In her second tour of duty in the state capital, she was the coordinator of the PVEM parliamentary group in the legislature.<ref name="sil"/> Meanwhile, she climbed the ranks in the PVEM, becoming technical secretary from 2011 to 2014 and secretary general from 2014 to 2017.<ref name="sil"/>

Voters returned Ávila to [[Palacio Legislativo de San Lázaro|San Lázaro]] in 2015. She is the secretary of the Northern Border Matters Commission and also serves on two other commissions, Metropolitan Development and Environment and Natural Resources.<ref name="sil"/> In order to return to the federal Chamber of Deputies, as specified by Article 190 of the Chihuahua state constitution, she was required to stand down as a state legislator.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nortedigital.mx/ongreso-del-estado-aprueba-separacion-de-maria-avila-serna/
|date=21 September 2015 |accessdate=8 July 2016 |work=Norte Digital |first=Ricardo|last=Espinoza|title=Congreso del Estado aprueba separación de María Ávila Serna|language=Spanish}}</ref>

==Personal==
Ávila is married to her third husband<ref name="omnia">{{cite news|url=http://www.omnia.com.mx/noticias/se-casa-maria-avila-por-tercera-ocasion/|title=Se casa María Ávila por tercera ocasión|date=25 July 2015|work=Omnia|accessdate=8 July 2016|language=Spanish|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925083059/http://www.omnia.com.mx/noticias/se-casa-maria-avila-por-tercera-ocasion/|archivedate=25 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and has four children, two from her first marriage.<ref name="diario">{{cite news|work=El Diario|url=http://diario.mx/micrositios/Elecciones-2015/candidato/MariaAvilaSerna/|title=Elecciones 2015: María Ávila Serna|accessdate=8 July 2016|language=Spanish}}</ref>[3] Two of her previous spouses were assassinated, in 2002 and 2005.<ref>{{cite news|work=La Jornada|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2010/04/29/politica/015n1pol|date=29 April 2010|accessdate=8 July 2016|first1=Rubén|last1=Villalpando|last2=Breach|first2=Miroslava|title=Matan a 29 personas en Juárez, incluidos cuatro estudiantes|language=Spanish}}</ref>

